{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535033"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15241"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.07,0.11,0.13,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87333"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7932"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2440"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8105"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87333"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a progressive ulcer on her left ankle. She lives in coastal Victoria and enjoys gardening. The ulcer began as a small painless nodule that gradually broke down. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm diameter ulcer with characteristic undermined edges on her left lateral malleolus. The base of the ulcer appears clean with some yellowish slough. The surrounding skin shows some purple discolouration. The ulcer is notably painless on palpation. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely implicated pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coxiella burnetii","Brucella","Bartonella henselae","Leishmania tropica","Mycobacterium ulcerans"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of Buruli ulcer. The key features supporting \u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium ulcerans\u003C/strong\u003E include the geographical location (coastal Victoria is endemic), painless nature of the ulcer, undermined edges, and the typical progression from a nodule to an ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmania tropica\u003C/strong\u003E causes cutaneous leishmaniasis, which can present with chronic ulcers. However, these typically occur in endemic regions such as the Middle East and North Africa, and are usually associated with sandfly exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrucella\u003C/strong\u003E rarely causes primary skin manifestations. When cutaneous involvement occurs, it is usually in the context of systemic brucellosis and presents with various non-specific lesions such as rashes, petechiae, or papules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes cat scratch disease, presenting with regional lymphadenopathy following a cat scratch or bite. While it can occasionally cause cutaneous manifestations, these are usually papules or pustules rather than large ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/strong\u003E is the causative organism of Q fever, which typically presents with systemic symptoms such as fever, headache, and myalgia. It does not typically cause primary skin manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EM. ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E infection requires specific treatment with a combination of antimycobacterial antibiotics (usually rifampicin and clarithromycin) for 8 weeks. Early diagnosis is crucial as delayed treatment can lead to extensive tissue destruction requiring surgical debridement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mycobacterium ulcerans causes painless ulcers with undermined edges, typically on exposed areas of the body.","The disease is endemic in specific geographical regions, particularly coastal Victoria in Australia.","Early diagnosis is crucial as treatment requires specific antimycobacterial therapy."],"references":["Wong CCW, Muhi S, O\u0027Brien D. An overview of Buruli ulcer in Australia. Aust J Gen Pract. 2024;53(9):671-674. doi:10.31128/AJGP-08-23-6914","Muhi S, Cox VRV, O\u0027Brien M, et al. Management of Mycobacterium ulcerans infection (Buruli ulcer) in Australia: consensus statement. MJA 20250223"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-27T14:23:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-27T14:23:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7932"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87333"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emo